4. The one real discrepancy — paper vs. code (in original TTT-Discover, faithfully reproduced by us)

The paper says "T ← T+1 after expanding parent p" and "n(a)+=1" — i.e. once per parent expansion. But because update_states/record_failed_rollout are called once per rollout (per child), T and n increment once per candidate, not once per parent. Empirically, one generation with a parent producing 3 valid + 1 failed child gives:

T = 4, n[parent] = 4   (paper's literal reading: T = 1, n[parent] = 1)
m[parent] = 0.9        (unaffected — max is idempotent)

So relative to a literal paper implementation, both T and n are inflated by ~`group_size. Effect on the search: m(s)(the exploitation term) is **identical**; only the exploration bonus√(1+T)/(1+n)` is rescaled — numerator grows as √(total candidates) while the denominator grows linearly in a node's candidate count, so heavily-sampled lineages are damped somewhat harder than the paper's node-level counting would. It's a consistent, monotone reweighting, not a bug that breaks the ranking. This lives in TTT-Discover's own code; since your directive was to reuse their strategy as faithfully as possible, our copy correctly preserves it.

Note: test_puct.py:41 passes both children in one update_states call, so it asserts T==1 — that hides this behavior because it doesn't replicate the per-rollout calling pattern the real loop uses. The test is internally correct; it just isn't exercising the drive pattern.

Verdict

The PUCT sampler is working exactly as the TTT-Discover implementation intends, and matches the paper's math precisely except for the per-candidate (vs. per-parent) counting of T/n, which is inherited verbatim from their code.


Em RL, o modelo é treinado com o reasoning + strategy + solution produzidas. Por isso, não é completamente justo darmos apenas as soluções finais ao modelo. Nas estratégias que estamos a usar acho que devíamos incluir também variações disto, para experimentarmos coisas diferentes.

Ao fazer ICL só com coisas de alto nível, podemos usar auto-compact nisto. ou usar apenas o reasoning + strategy sem solutions. ou só strategy...


